2152	2260	h	99152	1129	2017-06-06 18:40:43.790332	2022-03-08 18:25:34.679103	Freezing pressure	The positive pressure developed at ice-water interfaces in soil as it freezes. #{g: xqNSIDCCryosphere | h1635}\n\nThe positive pressure developed at ice-water interfaces in a soil as it freezes #{g: xqIPAPermafrost | h1630}\n\nThe positive pressure developed at ice-water interfaces in a soil as it freezes (freezing of in situ pore water - 9% expansion). It is also known to result in a heaving pressure or frost-heave pressure that is responsible for the heaving of utilities, foundations and pavements. Ice-water interfaces occur at the contact between Ice lenses and the Frozen Fringe. #{g: xqTrombottoGeocryology | h1639}\n\n#{g: xqGCW | h1619}		h2260	archived	vernacular	\N	\N
1879	1986	h	99152	1129	2017-06-06 17:53:11.514245	2022-03-08 18:25:35.944691	Cryogenic hygrometer	A special type of chilled mirror hygrometer capable of measuring very low frost points. These low temperatures at the mirror are attained by evaporating low boiling point or cryogenic fluids. This strong cooling capability allows cryogenic hygrometers to maintain reasonable response times even at low frost points. Cryogenic hygrometers are used for airborne humidity measurements from aircraft or balloons, but also in semiconductor industries for monitoring very dry environmental conditions needed in manufacturing processes. #{g: xqAMSglossary | h1620}\n\n#{g: xqGCW | h1619}		h1986	archived	vernacular	\N	\N
2207	2315	h	99152	1129	2017-06-06 18:43:22.606649	2022-03-08 18:25:36.841927	Frostless zone	That warmest part of a slope above a valley floor lying between the layer of cold air that forms over the valley floor on calm, clear nights and the cold hilltops or plateaus. The air flowing down the slopes is warmed by mixing with the air above ground level and to some extent also by adiabatic compression. The frostless zone is not a fixed belt but varies in level from night to night and season to season according to the initial temperature, the length of the night, and the clearness of the sky. Its lower limit is sometimes clearly marked by the upper limit of frost damage to crops, following the hillsides at a small angle to the horizontal. (Also called thermal belt, thermal zone, green belt, verdant zone.) #{g: xqAMSglossary | h1620}\n\n#{g: xqGCW | h1619}		h2315	archived	vernacular	\N	\N
2144	2252	h	99152	1129	2017-06-06 18:40:22.702872	2022-03-08 18:25:38.055075	Freezing drizzle	Drizzle, the drops of which freeze on impact with the ground or with objects at or near the ground. #{g: xqCanadaNCA | h1624}\n\nDrizzle, the drops of which freeze on impact with the ground or with objects on the earth's surface or with aircraft in flight. #{g: xqNSIDCCryosphere | h1635}\n\nA drizzle that falls as a liquid but freezes into glaze or rime upon contact with the cold ground or surface structures. #{g: xqNOAA-NWS | h1633}\n\nDrizzle that freezes on impact to form a coating of clear ice (glaze) on the ground and on exposed objects. #{g: xqECCCanada | h1625}\n\nDrizzle that falls in liquid form but freezes upon impact to form a coating of glaze. In U.S. aviation weather observations, this hydrometeor is encoded ZL. The physical cause of this phenomenon is the same as that for freezing rain. #{g: xqAMSglossary | h1620}\n\nDrizzle, the drops of which freeze on impact with the ground or with objects on the earth's surface or with aircraft in flight. #{g: xqSPRI | h1637}\n\n#{g: xqGCW | h1619}		h2252	archived	vernacular	\N	\N
