2486	2594	h	99152	1129	2017-06-06 19:03:13.681174	2022-03-08 18:26:26.348895	Ice prisms	A fall of unbranched ice crystals, in the form of needles, columns, or plates, often so tiny that they seem to be suspended in the air; these are visible mainly when they glitter in the sunshine (diamond dust); they may then produce a luminous pillar or other halo phenomena; this hydrometeor, which is frequent in polar regions, occurs at very low temperatures and in stable air masses. #{g: xqNSIDCCryosphere | h1635}\n\nUnbranched prismatic ice crystals, in the form of needles, columns or plates, often so tiny that they seem to be suspended in the air. These crystals may fall from a cloud or from a cloudless sky. #{g: xqWMOMeteoterm | h1643}\n\nIce crystals having well defined crystalline facets, usually on both basal planes and on prism planes. #{g: xqAMSglossary | h1620}\n\nA fall of unbranched ice crystals, in the form of needles, columns or plates, often so tiny that they seem to be suspended in the air. These crystals may fall from a cloud or from a cloudless sky. They are visible mainly when they glitter in the sunshine (diamond dust); they may then produce a luminous pillar or other halo phenomena. This hydrometeor, which is frequent in polar regions, occurs at very low temperatures and in stable air masses. #{g: xqSPRI | h1637}\n\n#{g: xqGCW | h1619}		h2594	archived	vernacular	\N	\N
