3241	3349	h	99152	1129	2017-06-06 19:40:00.449857	2022-03-08 18:27:38.599676	Snow density	The mass of snow per unit volume which is equal to the water content of the snow divided by its depth. #{g: xqNOAAHydrology | h1634}\n\nThe mass of snow per unit volume which is equal to the water content of snow divided by its depth. #{g: xqNSIDCCryosphere | h1635}\n\nSee relative density. #{g: xqIACSSnow | h1628}\n\nThe mass of snow per unit volume which is equal to the water content of the snow divided by its depth. #{g: xqNOAA-NWS | h1633}\n\nMass of snowpack per unit volume. #{g: xqWMOHydrology | h1642}\n\nThe ratio of the volume of meltwater that can be derived from a sample of snow to the original volume of the sample; strictly speaking, this is the specific gravity of the snow sample. Freshly fallen snow usually has a snow density of 0.07 to 0.15; glacial ice formed from compacted snow (or firn) has a maximum density of about 0.91. Values as low as 0.004 have been measured. #{g: xqAMSglossary | h1620}\n\n#{g: xqGCW | h1619}		h3349	archived	vernacular	\N	\N
