3633	3741	h	99152	1129	2017-06-06 19:54:47.624899	2022-03-08 18:39:39.407749	Weathering	Processes of ablation and accumulation that gradually eliminate irregularities in an ice surface. #{g: xqWMOSeaIce | h1644}\n\nSea ice terminology. Describes the processes of ablation and accumulation, which gradually eliminate irregularities in an ice surface. #{g: xqECCCanada | h1625}\n\nThe mechanical, chemical, or biological action of the atmosphere, hydrometeors, and suspended impurities on the form, color, or constitution of exposed material; to be distinguished from erosion. Mechanical weathering results from the disintegrating action of high or low temperature, large changes of temperature, frost, or the impact of wind-borne sand or water (e.g., frost action, scouring, etc.). Chemical weathering is due to the chemical action of atmospheric constituents, especially acid impurities, in a moist atmosphere or in rainwater (e.g. corrosion, oxidation, etc.). Biological agents are mainly fungi that attack organic material (e.g., rotting, mildew, etc.). #{g: xqAMSglossary | h1620}\n\nThe processes of ablation and accumulation which gradually eliminate irregularities in an ice surface. #{g: xqSPRI | h1637}\n\n#{g: xqGCW | h1619}		h3741	archived	vernacular	\N	\N
