4062	4179	h	99152	1129	2022-03-08 18:22:55.244891	2022-04-08 03:42:33.51171	Ice cap	A dome-shaped mass of glacier ice, usually situated in a highland area, and generally defined as covering up to 50,000 square kilometres (cf. ice sheet). 	\N	h4179	published	vernacular	\N	\N
4063	4180	h	99152	1129	2022-03-08 18:22:55.340333	2022-04-08 03:42:33.51171	Ice cap	A dome-shaped perennial cover of ice and snow over an extensive portion of the earth's surface. Ice caps are considerably smaller than ice sheets, and it is felt improper to refer to the Greenland and Antarctic Ice Sheets as ice caps. Most ice caps are most probably remnants of the Quaternary Ice Age. The term was first used for the supposedly perennial ice cover at both poles of the earth. However, since it has been found that the ice of arctic waters is largely seasonal, the use of this term to denote arctic polar ice is now considered improper. 	\N	h4180	published	vernacular	\N	\N
